        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Nov 17 1871</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>As you give me the choice, have 1000 of the Descent printed &amp; please to see that the number of the <hi rend="underline">thousandth</hi> on the title page is altered.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>As I shall make no alteration I shall put you to no expense.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> If the book goes on selling it will shew that it is worth a thorough revision.</p>
<p>Thank you for telling me about the sale of the other books.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> Proofs of the Origin come in slow: if the price is kept low I much hope &amp; expect that it will have a good sale.<ref target="#foot.f4"/> I have asked Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Clowes to send me duplicate revises, as 2 foreign translations are waiting for correction.<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>They have beaten us in the U. States in the sale of the Descent as some time ago they had sold 10,000 copies<ref target="#foot.f6"/></p>
<p>My dear Sir | yours sincerely | Ch Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.2 of the <hi rend="italic">thousandth</hi>] <hi rend="italic">interl in CD’s hand</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">4.1 in … Descent] <hi rend="italic">interl in CD’s hand</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8071.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from R. F. Cooke, 16 November 1871</ref>. The fourth printing of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> appeared in December 1871 with the figure ‘eighth thousand’ on the title page (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2661.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1977</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In fact, CD did introduce small changes into the fourth printing (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2661.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1977</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8071.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from R. F. Cooke, 16 November 1871</ref> and n. 2.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD, with the assistance of his son <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1245.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Erasmus Darwin</ref>, was going over the proofs of the sixth edition of <hi rend="italic">Origin.</hi> It was printed with smaller type and sold at the reduced price of 7<hi rend="italic">s.</hi> 6<hi rend="italic">d.</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2661.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1977</ref>, p. 79).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">New French and German translations (Moulinié trans. 1873, Bronn and Carus trans. 1872) were being prepared from the text of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6019.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 6th ed.</ref> See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7859.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. J. Moulinié, 12 July [1871]</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7994.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. V. Carus, 8 October [1871]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">The US edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> was published by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_135.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">D. Appleton &amp; Co</ref>mpany.</note>
        </div>        
            
